{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1264"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1264"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.16,0.04,0.7,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79756"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1264"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65060"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44047"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79756"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of vomiting, diarrhoea, fevers, and abdominal pain. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and uses an insulin pump. She takes no other regular medications. She denies alcohol or recreational drug use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and pale. Her pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.9\u00b0C. Her abdomen is diffusely tender with guarding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous blood gas analysis reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.04 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 30 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 16 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.3 mmol/L (3.5-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate 2 mmol/L (0.5-2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose 32 mmol/L (2.0-6.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV potassium replacement","IV insulin infusion","IV sodium bicarbonate","IV fluid resuscitation","IV antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) precipitated by gastroenteritis, evidenced by hyperglycaemia, acidosis, and a typical clinical presentation. The severity is indicated by the marked acidosis (pH 7.04) and hyperglycaemia (32 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step. Patients with DKA are typically several litres fluid-depleted due to osmotic diuresis and vomiting. Adequate fluid replacement improves tissue perfusion, reduces stress hormones, and helps correct acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV potassium replacement\u003C/strong\u003E will be necessary as total body potassium is depleted in DKA, and insulin therapy will further lower serum potassium. However, this is not the first priority unless potassium is severely low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV insulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is essential for treating DKA but should follow initial fluid resuscitation. Insulin helps correct hyperglycaemia and ketosis but may be less effective if the patient remains severely dehydrated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated in DKA, even with severe acidosis. The acidosis typically resolves with fluid replacement and insulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as the clinical picture is consistent with viral gastroenteritis. There are no specific features suggesting bacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial fluid resuscitation, management should include regular monitoring of electrolytes, glucose, and clinical status, with insulin therapy commenced according to local DKA protocols.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IV fluid resuscitation is the most important first step in diabetic ketoacidosis management, even before insulin therapy.","Diabetic ketoacidosis commonly presents with significant dehydration requiring several litres of fluid replacement.","Infection, particularly gastroenteritis, is a common precipitant of diabetic ketoacidosis."],"references":["Castellanos L, Tuffaha M, Koren D, Levitsky LL. Management of Diabetic Ketoacidosis in Children and Adolescents with Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus. Paediatr Drugs. 2020;22(4):357-67. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32449138/","Chua HR, Venkatesh B, Stachowski E, Schneider AG, Perkins K, et al. Plasma-Lyte 148 vs 0.9% saline for fluid resuscitation in diabetic ketoacidosis.\u00a0J Crit Care. 2012;27(2):138\u201345. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22440386/","Ferriss B, O\u2019Hare J, Kelleher C, Sullivan P, Cole, the al. Diabetic Control and the Renin-Angiotensin System, Catecholamines, and Blood Pressure.\u00a0Hypertension. 1985;7(6):II58-63. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3935582/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65060"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1264"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65060"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T14:35:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T14:35:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1264"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79756"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"